345–1391":"1345–1391","about 1370":"about 1370","20 January 1382":"20 January 1382","1352":"1352","1383":"about 1391","1382":"1382","1370":"1370","1391":"1391","1369":"about 1369","1346":"1346","1345":"1345","1365":"1365","1418":"1418","1417":"1417","Castle Whalesborough, Cornwall, England":"Whalesborough, Cornwall, England","Whalesborough, Cornwall, England":"Whalesborough, Cornwall, England","Whalesborough Manor, Cornwall, England":"Whalesborough, Cornwall, England, United Kingdom","Elford, Staffordshire, England":"Elford, Staffordshire, England","Pilkington, Lancashire, England":"Pilkington, Lancashire, England","Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Pilkington","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (northwestern): habitational name from a place in Lancashire. The placename may derive from an Old English personal name <i>Pīleca</i> or <i>Pīloc</i> + patronymic <i>-ing</i> + Old English <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’. The surname is established in Ireland, where its presence was first recorded in the early 15th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Pilkerton","meanings":["English: variant of   Pilkington  ."]},{"name":"Pilkinton","meanings":["English: variant of   Pilkington  ."]},{"name":"Pilkenton","meanings":["English: variant of   Pilkington  ."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":37,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Margaret Pilkington was born in 1345, in Pilkington, Lancashire, England. She married Sir John Whalesborough in 1365, in Cornwall, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. She died about 1391, in Elford, Staffordshire, England, at the age of 47."},"et":{"1345–1383":"1345–umbes 1391","1346–1382":"1346–1382","1352–Male":"1352–Surnud","1369–1418":"umbes1369–1418","1370–1417":"1370–1417","1345–1391":"1345–1391","about 1370":"umbes 1370","20 January 1382":"20. jaanuar 1382","1352":"1352","1383":"umbes 1391","1382":"1382","1370":"1370","1391":"1391","1369":"umbes 1369","1346":"1346","1345":"1345","1365":"1365","1418":"1418","1417":"1417","Castle Whalesborough, Cornwall, England":"Whalesborough, Cornwall, England","Whalesborough, Cornwall, England":"Whalesborough, Cornwall, England","Whalesborough Manor, Cornwall, England":"Whalesborough, Cornwall, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Elford, Staffordshire, England":"Elford, Staffordshire, England","Pilkington, Lancashire, England":"Pilkington, Lancashire, England","Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1345–1383":"1345–noin 1391","1346–1382":"1346–1382","1352–Male":"1352–Kuollut","1369–1418":"noin1369–1418","1370–1417":"1370–1417","1345–1391":"1345–1391","about 1370":"noin 1370","20 January 1382":"20. tammikuuta 1382","1352":"1352","1383":"noin 1391","1382":"1382","1370":"1370","1391":"1391","1369":"noin 1369","1346":"1346","1345":"1345","1365":"1365","1418":"1418","1417":"1417","Castle Whalesborough, Cornwall, England":"Whalesborough, Cornwall, England","Whalesborough, Cornwall, England":"Whalesborough, Cornwall, England","Whalesborough Manor, Cornwall, England":"Whalesborough, Cornwall, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Elford, Staffordshire, England":"Elford, Staffordshire, Engla